<br>
Masakato sat in a small grove in Surefall Glade, meditating and reflecting on the day's occurrences. Not far off, Natil sat quietly beside her babysitter, the druid Crystal, enthralled by the dance of two colorful butterflies. Zariel had left to take a last swim, but Masakato had stayed to keep watch over her young daughter. The child's laughter and smile brought a warmth to his soul. <br>
Looking at the setting sun, Crystal said, &quot;It is time for Natil's feeding, and then bed. We will see you tomorrow morning, Brother.&quot; Crystal picked Natil up. The young child giggled as the young druid spun her around in the air. “I’ll miss Zariel. I’ll miss you too,” she added. <br>
The taciturn monk smiled slightly and nodded. He opened one eye and grinned as he watched the pair head to the cabin. But soon the smile turned to a frown as Masakato sat there, listening. <br>
<br>
Silence. <br>
<br>
Dead silence. <br>
<br>
The sound of a broken twig sent the monk quickly to his feet, but instantly he was engulfed by shadows. Panic struck then, but Masakato quickly regained his composure. He stood there, fists ready, concentrating. Sensing an unknown presence near, he spun around striking at his would-be attacker. The blow knocked the dark figure back. &quot;Heh.&quot; The dark figure chuckled, &quot;A lucky hit. Come, monk. Let us dance.&quot; The figure leapt at the monk, his dark blade hungry to inflict pain. Masakato landed a few kicks and punches, <br>
But this dark stranger was obviously more experienced and he knew he was facing a losing battle. Suddenly, the stranger's fist cast an eerie glow and Masakato's body was gripped in agony by some dark force. Masakato fell to the ground, his consciousness fading fast. The last thing he saw was a rolled<br>
parchment fall from the dark stranger's hand. <br>
*** *** *** <br>
<br>
Zariel walked through Surefall Glade. She had just taken what she knew would be the last swim in the pure waters of Surefall Glade for a long time. She had taken longer than usual, trying to preserve the memory in her mind, against her coming trials. A gentle breeze blew fallen leaves into her wet hair. As she stopped to pull them out, a chill raced up her spine. The wind suddenly became colder. Zariel looked about waiting for an unknown enemy to leap from the dark shadows. Nothing. Quickly Zariel dismissed the thought, surely it was just the change of seasons. Or the wind on her body, which still glistened with water from her swim.<br>
Zariel made her way home, the last few moments a fleeting thought. She opened the door to find the room surprisingly dark. Lighting a lantern, Zariel gasped in horror. Crystal, one of the rangers left to watch <br>
Natil, sat at the dining table - dead. Her neck was sliced open, the gash resembling a cruel smile. Her mouth was locked in a mute scream and her eyes stared at the last vision of horror she had seen. The note Zariel had left to send to the Council was gone, as was her hawk, Onyx. <br>
Panic stuck Zariel like a bolt of thunder. <br>
<br>
Natil. <br>
<br>
Running into her bedroom, she stopped dead at the doorway. Natil laid there, giggling. Holding onto her was a knight dressed in the purest black of armor. <br>
<br>
&quot;Drazhkahn.&quot;<br>
