<br>
&quot;Ah! The monk returns,&quot; Drazhkahn grinned. &quot;Go ahead young one.&quot; he said looking down at Natil. &quot;Say it.&quot;<br>
&quot;Vin-doo-ee&quot; Natil said. Drazhkahn smiled in delight at the look of horror that crossed Zariel's face.<br>
&quot;She is a quick learner, this one is. She must have gotten it from her father's side.&quot; Drazhkahn grinned, daring Zariel to lunge at him. Zariel took one step towards Drazhkahn, her fists curled tight, the knuckles turning white. &quot;Go ahead young monk, and it will be the last word your daughter says,&quot; Drazhkahn said as he held the child in front of him and tickled her. Natil's giggling made Zariel's heart race. <br>
&quot;What is it that you want?&quot; Zariel asked.<br>
&quot;What a lovely daughter you have here,&quot; Drazhkahn replied, ignoring Zariel’s question. &quot;But why you neglect her by leaving her with such careless fools is beyond me.&quot;<br>
&quot;If you harm her I will --&quot; Zariel said through clenched teeth.<br>
&quot;I think you are not in the position to be giving threats. But what a conundrum this is, whatever shall you do?&quot;<br>
&quot;Give her to me,&quot; said Zariel slowly, reaching out. Her voice was calm, but Drazhkahn could see the flash of panic in her eyes. &quot;Give her back.&quot;<br>
&quot;I don't think so,&quot; replied the Shadow Knight silkily. &quot;Hold still, monk, or I will kill her.&quot; Zariel froze. Drazhkahn smiled. &quot;That's a good girl.&quot;<br>
&quot;What is it that you want?&quot; Zariel repeated. Drazhkahn shook his head.<br>
&quot;Dense you are,&quot; he said, &quot;like all other humans. It should be obvious what I want.&quot;<br>
&quot;Mama?&quot; said the little girl suddenly. &quot;Mama!&quot; she reached out to Zariel, who remained still, a look of intense pain on her face. Natil began to fuss. Drazhkahn tickled her again, and she calmed down.<br>
&quot;Now, Zarry,&quot; began Drazhkahn.<br>
Predictably, Zariel flared. &quot;Don't call me that! That name is not for you to use!&quot;<br>
&quot;I believe I said you were in no position to make threats?&quot; Drazhkahn said. &quot;Yes, and no position to make demands either. I will call you what I like.&quot; Zariel glared, but remained silent. &quot;Now...Zarry...as to what I want, I think I will not tell you yet. But there is something others want. Tell me, does the name Reionik sound familiar?&quot; The young woman's response to that surprised even the usually imperturbable Drazhkahn. He watched in interest as Zariel suddenly doubled over, as if in a spasm of pain. A muffled moan escaped her. &quot;I see it does,&quot; said Drazhkahn. &quot;And of course, there are Natil's father's interests.&quot;<br>
At that, Zariel straightened up, glaring at Drazhkahn in defiance. &quot;She has no father.&quot;<br>
&quot;That is not what I hear,&quot; Drazhkahn mocked the helpless monk. &quot;There are some that are interested in your child. I am interested in the mother. I will take your child to them. If you want to see her again, I recommend you come too -- quietly.&quot; Zariel glared at the Shadow Knight, but nodded her head in agreement. &quot;Here,&quot; Drazhkahn said, tossing Zariel a bottle of clear, red liquid. &quot;Drink its contents in their entirety.&quot;<br>
Zariel looked at the bottle, then at Drazhkahn. Her eyes narrowed suspiciously.<br>
Drazhkahn laughed, &quot;It is not poison, I assure you; it is merely to make sure our journey is a safe one. Now drink or I will leave you here with an empty cradle.&quot;<br>
Zariel frowned at the Tier'dal's words. She looked down at the bottle and drank down its contents. It tasted sweet, like honey, but then a burning sensation overcame her as the liquid raced down her throat. Her stomach felt warm as she gasped for air, trying to quench the fire that seemed to be ablaze in her mouth.<br>
&quot;What was this?&quot; Zariel asked. The room seemed to shift and move.<br>
&quot;It is nothing but Neriak's finest, my sweet.&quot; Drazhkahn said, as his image became blurred and distorted. &quot;Now this may hurt a bit...&quot;<br>
&quot;Mama. NO!&quot; Natil cried out, but Zariel's reactions were dulled and the last thing she felt was the hilt of the Shadow Knight's reaver against her head.<br>
Darkness welcomed her like an old friend.<br>
