<br>
&quot;Masakato! Masakato, my friend. Are you alright?&quot; The voice was that of Ran, one of the Rangers who watched over Surefall Glade. &quot;Huh?&quot; Masakato asked as the man helped him to sit upright.<br>
&quot;I was on my way back from Qeynos,&quot; Ran replied, &quot;and I noticed signs of a struggle. I fear I have bad news, my friend. Crystal is dead, and Zariel and her daughter are...missing. I could find no tracks; all I have found is you and this letter.&quot; Ran's face was creased with pain as he spoke of Crystal; Masakato could tell it took all Ran's strength to keep from weeping.<br>
Masakato himself was filled with grief when he heard the news. He was supposed to have watched Natil, to have protected her. His hands shaking lightly, he took the parchment and unrolled it.<br>
It read: <br>
I have the child of Innoruuk and her mother. You need not look for them. They are now lost to you, but your Sister will fulfill my needs immensely. Do not be so foolish as to assault Neriak. By the time you reach the Third Gate, the child will be gone and her mother will be swinging from the hooks of Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
The missive looked to have been written in blood.<br>
Masakato looked up from the letter, his sorrow turning to grim determination. &quot;Arikel. I must get this letter to Arikel.&quot;<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udrazhkahn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Drazhkahn</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/1/00 1:07:10 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Taken (continued...)</span><hr size=1> Part 4: The Dream <br>
<br>
The darkness was slowly swallowed by a brilliant, white light. Zariel's eyes slowly adjusted to the change, but she rubbed them as she looked about the scene before her. She stood in the middle of what appeared to be the final moments of a large battle but everything was devoid of color. Shades of grey and white stood in contrast to the dense blacks, as a large group of white armored knights surrounded a lone knight in black. The white knights were all faceless, their features wiped away leaving a pale, blank appearance, but the black knight - he had a visage. Zariel's hands curled into fists as she looked at the dark knight. It was Drazhkahn. The large group of warriors surrounded him as he knelt over the corpse of a female Tier'dal. Black tears stained his grey skin as he held the dead female in his arms. Zariel refused to believe that he could feel such sorrow. Zariel stood close by, ignored by all as the scene played out before her, the faceless knights surrounding Drazhkahn, their weapons drawn and ready. Drazhkahn's pain turned to blind rage as he leapt at his enemies. His fury fell three of them but the battle was short lived as the rest quickly overpowered him. He winced in pain as a spear pierced his back; the point glistened with his glossy, black blood as it ripped through his chestplate. Blade strokes bit into his armor and flesh and soon, the dark knight fell to the ground.<br>
Zariel watched as Drazhkahn crawled to the female Teir'dal, his life quickly feeding the hungry soil. He reached out to her, his hand only inches away from her final resting-place….<br>
Time and space seemed to slow as a large axe blade swept down to end the Shadow Knight. Drazhkahn desperately reached out, oblivious to his inevitable demise. As the blade struck the knight, the sorrow and pain of a thousand lost loves wailed in Zariel's mind as a brilliant flash of white light blinded her again.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udrazhkahn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Drazhkahn</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/2/00 3:36:45 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Taken (continued...)</span><hr size=1> Part 5: Neriak<br>
<br>
Zariel woke and leapt from a large ornate bed. She glanced around, looking for her daughter, but the sudden quickness sent a rush of blood to her clouded mind. She stumbled as her hangover worsened and the room spun briefly out of control. She held the sides of her head as she looked around.<br>
&quot;This certainly isn't Surefall.&quot; Zariel muttered.<br>
A fireplace roared on one side of the room, the mantle resembling the maw of some foul demon. Tapestries and ornate shields adorned the walls, depicting hideous scenes of bloodshed and death. A large yeowood chest stuck out, an odd contrast to the bronze and obsidian. Curious, Zariel went over to the chest. Locked. She wondered what a chest, so obviously out of place, was doing in such a dark-hearted room.<br>
Suddenly the large, bronze double doors swung open. Zariel stood and spun around, one leg lashing out in a round kick automatically. Drazhkahn, however, seemed to have expected this, and she missed him entirely.<br>
&quot;Ahhh. I see that you are awake,&quot; Drazhkahn said with a sly grin. &quot;I take it you are comfortable with your new attire?&quot;<br>
In her perplexed state, Zariel had not realized that she was no longer wearing her armor; she was dressed in shimmering gossamer cloth. It felt smooth to the touch and seemed to radiate a light, white glow. It must have been crafted by the hands of a master tailor, for the seams and stitching were completely hidden.<br>
&quot;Where is my armor?&quot; she demanded, gazing at the dress in disdain. &quot;Give me back my gi! Monks don't wear dresses -- I certainly don't wear dresses!&quot; Suddenly, the expression on her face changed from disdain, to revulsion, to outright horror. &quot;How,&quot; she said hoarsely, &quot;did I get out of my armor and into this dress?&quot; Zariel looked around her wildly, afraid to see what might rest in Drazhkahn's eyes, a dull flush spreading from her neck to her cheeks, where it flamed red for a moment before she forced it down. Suddenly, her azure eyes flew wide. &quot;Natil!&quot; she cried. &quot;Where is my daughter? Give her to me!&quot;<br>
&quot;Not even a thanks.&quot; Drazhkahn frowned, &quot;After all the trouble I went through.&quot;<br>
&quot;Thanks?&quot; Zariel exclaimed, her face growing hot again. &quot;For what? You are the one that has taken my daughter from me! Now where is she?&quot;<br>
&quot;As you wish.&quot; Drazhkahn said as a young Fier'dal chambermaid entered, holding Natil's hands, helping the little girl to walk.<br>
&quot;Mommy!&quot; Natil exclaimed, her eyes sparkling in delight. She was dressed in a small green silk robe and lotus blossoms adorned her head like a crown.<br>
Zariel ran to Natil and clutched her in her arms. Neither Drazhkahn nor the chambermaid stopped her. She held her daughter close. &quot;What is it you want from us?&quot; Zariel asked, looking up at Drazhkahn, &quot;Where are we?&quot;<br>
&quot;That I can answer monk,&quot; Drazhkahn replied. &quot;You are deep within the city of Neriak, where only a few have the privilege to gain access to. There are no guards within these walls for there is no need; to enter and leave you need to be imbued with a certain mark, a mark that neither you nor Natil possess. But I doubt you will want to travel the streets of Neriak anyway; the guards will not take your presence lightly, especially if you carry a Tier'dal child with you. But feel free to wander about the halls and rooms of the guildhouse. If you require anything, tell one of the slaves and they shall oblige you, but unfortunately, they have a small vocabulary so conversation will not be easy.&quot; He grinned evilly as he glanced at the Fier'dal slave. The slave looked down at the floor as she opened her mouth.<br>
Half of her tongue had been cut off. Drazhkahn seemed amused at the look of sympathy Zariel gave the slave girl.<br>
&quot;Yes, to avoid capture, most of them preferred to swallow their own tongues.&quot; Drazhkahn continued, &quot;Now, it is seen to that they are not given that luxury. Drazhkahn looked down towards Zariel. &quot;I will have no qualms of doing the same to you if you do not cooperate.&quot; Zariel hugged Natil even closer; she wasn't going to let Natil from her sight anymore, and this monster wasn't going to take her away again!<br>
&quot;Now I have a small matter I must attend to. If you travel into the kitchen, please be careful of the ogres. They have a fondness for human flesh and it would be a shame for you to lose an arm because you got too close. I shall return upon the new moon. Then we can discuss what is to come.&quot;<br>
With that Drazhkahn left the bedroom, closing the double doors behind him.<br>
<br>
He left mother and daughter deep within the dark city of Neriak.<br>
<br>
Alone.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udrazhkahn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Drazhkahn</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/7/00 10:56:06 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Taken (continued...)</span><hr size=1> Part 6: The Warmth of the Hearth<br>
<br>
Drazhkahn stormed into the banquet hall, his eyes burning with hatred and his skin red-hot. &quot;There you are!&quot; Drazhkahn yelled as he pointed to a young necromantic apprentice. &quot;How dare you!&quot; The young necromancer looked about for help as the others sat there, watching the drama unfold.<br>
&quot;There are many that believe she is tainted,” the necromancer replied. &quot;She must be destr..ugh.&quot;<br>
The necromancer's words were cut short as Drazhkahn lifted him out of his chair and sent him flying headfirst into the fireplace mantle. His head made a sickening crack upon the stone, and a crimson streak painted the stone as he slumped down to the marble floor. He then lay there near the fire, groaning in agony.<br>
Drazhkahn knelt beside him, a look of concern over his face. He moved his hand gently over the necromancer's jawline, wiping away the blood that trickled down from the wound near his temple. Suddenly, Drazhkahn’s face turned dark, a snarl etched across his lips. His grip tightened around the young man's neck as he pushed his head into the roaring fire.<br>
A sudden cry echoed across the chamber. &quot;Stop! Stop it!&quot; Zariel screamed, horror plain in her voice. &quot;Stop, please!&quot; She rose to her feet, but did not -- dared not -- move. Drazhkahn did not seem to hear her; he certainly did not acknowledge her. The young monk's pleas did no good. Sitting again, she pulled her knees up to her chest, burying her face against them as she began to sob.<br>
Screams of terror and pain erupted from the blaze as the young necromancer's hair and flesh caught fire. Zariel clapped her hands to her ears, trying to block out the sound. The necromancer flailed his arms wildly, searching for a means to escape Drazhkahn's wrath, but the grip of the Shadow Knight held. Within minutes, the pleas and cries for help were extinguished.<br>
Drazhkahn held up the remains of the necromancer; his eyes had melted, his hair was gone, the flesh charred and peeling. The smell of burnt flesh filled the room. Zariel was still shaking with tears, her hands still over her ears, as though she could somehow block out what had happened.<br>
