<br>
&quot;Let us get one thing, straight, Dark Elf,&quot; hissed Zariel. Drazhkahn watched her with amusement. She was striding back and forth across the room accorded her at the guildhouse of the Children of Darkness. She was obviously very angry. Both fists were clenched tightly, and he could tell by her walk that she was battle ready. Her every muscle was clenched, from her jaw to her feet in their slippers of soft leather. No sense letting her have boots; after all, she wouldn't be going outside. The green dress she wore swirled around her legs, occasionally clinging to thigh or hip in a way that was almost provocative. She had not asked for her armor back since the first day, but Drazhkahn could tell she was still as unhappy in dresses as ever. It was this, along with her determination not to hit him, that he found so humorous.<br>
Suddenly, Zariel rushed at him, stopping just short of touching him. She was tall, even for a human, and had a good six inches on her captor, which now she used to her full advantage. He was not scared a bit. <br>
&quot;She is not your daughter!&quot; the monk yelled. Drazhkahn, not moving, arched one silver-white eyebrow. &quot;Natil is _my_ daughter! Mine and no one else's, and most certainly not yours!&quot;<br>
Breathing deeply, Zariel stepped back. She longed to spit at him, that supercilious piece of filth. Calling Natil his daughter, and in front of his whole bloody (literally, in some cases) guild, no less! How could he? How dared he! Zariel was shaking with suppressed rage. More than spitting at him, she wanted to hit him. She had given that monster, Reionik, a black eye, and it had been one of the more satisfying moments of her life. The price the necromancer had extracted had been worth it. Yet she dared not hit Drazhkahn; in fact, she really hardly dared to talk back to him. She could not do anything that would endanger innocents.<br>
Zariel was no fool, and she knew he would not dare to harm Natil. Drazhkahn believed that Natil was the daughter of his god, Innoruuk. Completely impossible, of course, but he insisted upon it. That particular delusion was fine with Zariel, as it kept Natil perfectly safe. Furthermore, Zariel felt fairly sure Drazhkahn would not hurt her, and if he did, she knew she could stand it. He would not kill her, nor maim her, so Natil would not be left an orphan, and Zariel would not be incapable of caring for her once they escaped. However, she knew there were other innocents in this house of horrors. She did not doubt for a minute that Drazhkahn would take his anger out on a Fier'Dal servant, and favor Zariel with all the details later. Or worse, he would force her to watch, to hear the inarticulate screams that were no doubt pleas for mercy. And she would be unable to stop him, or to spare the poor victim any pain. Therefore, she restrained herself.<br>
Drazhkahn's eyes seemed to dance, daring her to act. &quot;Say you so?&quot; he asked, his voice smooth, almost a purr, almost seductive. Zariel looked away. &quot;I do not think I like your attitude, monk,&quot; Drazhkahn went on, sneering. &quot;We have had this discussion before, have we not? About who is in a position to make demands, and who is not?&quot; She said nothing. &quot;Answer me,&quot; he snarled, his voice like a whip crack.<br>
&quot;Yes,&quot; she said, grinding her teeth.<br>
&quot;And who did we decide was in a position to make demands?&quot; he asked, his voice silky once more.<br>
&quot;You,&quot; she spat, hating every moment of this. She thought of the pain and torture she might be sparing another person. That was why she was doing this, and it was enough reason. Who knew what depraved things he did as part of his everyday routine, things her mind could not even dream of? She could not look at him; no matter why she was doing this, shame burned inside her. But, bright stars in the firmament, he had burned a man to death in the middle of dinner last night!<br>
Drazhkahn was enjoying this. He was not certain why Zariel had suddenly become so tractable, but he could guess. He could also tell that this behavior did not make her happy; in fact, it shamed her and made her miserable. Drazhkahn was pleased. One way or another, she would learn to obey him, to accept what was to come. What he knew had to come. Innoruuk had not made a mistake in choosing this woman for the mother of His child; he had made a mistake in allowing Reionik to be His instrument. <br>
Zariel's brother Arikel, who Drazhkahn hated more than any other person, had saved her too quickly. There had not been time to corrupt her. But now Drazhkahn had her, and there was no way her brother, or any of her guild, could get to her.<br>
&quot;Now, let us get one _more_ thing straight, Human,&quot; he said, mocking her earlier words.<br>
She turned to look at him, her eyes narrowed. &quot;I...have...a...name,&quot; she growled from between gritted teeth.<br>
&quot;Yes, I know...Zarry,&quot; he said, his voice almost a caress.<br>
&quot;Zariel!&quot; she cried. &quot;My name is Zariel, to you!&quot;<br>
&quot;I will call you what I please,&quot; he informed her shortly. &quot;It does not please me to call you Zariel. It is such a hard name, for one so tender.&quot; She glared at him, but said no more. &quot;Now, repeat after me: Drazhkahn is Natil's father.&quot;<br>
&quot;I will not! You are not!&quot; cried Zariel, horror and revulsion on her face. Drazhkahn sighed. He had not really expected her to acquiesce. &quot;She has no father! Only me! There was no father! And even if there was, it would never in a million years be you!&quot;<br>
&quot;There was then, and there is now, monk!&quot; Drazhkahn shouted back. &quot;And there always will be, and he is I!&quot; Drazhkahn turned his back on her and stormed out. It did not matter if he had not sired the child, couldn't she see? Was she as blind and foolish as all her kind? Natil certainly looked more like him than she did like Zariel! Natil was his child, his daughter. Outside the chamber, he cornered the Fier'Dal chambermaid who was bringing in a freshly bathed Natil to see her mother.<br>
&quot;Not today,&quot; said Drazhkahn shortly in Tier'Dal. &quot;Today I will spend with my daughter. Her Tier'Dal is not as proficient as it should be, since her mother makes her speak Common. Vendui, beauty,&quot; he added, turning to the little girl, using her mother's favorite pet name for her, &quot;How are you today?&quot;<br>
Looking up at him with eyes like pools, as deep, as blue, and as innocent as her mother's, Natil replied, &quot;Ven-dwee, Dwaz-kan!&quot;<br>
&quot;Today,&quot; Drazhkahn said, casually shoving the chambermaid out of his way, &quot;we're going to learn a new word. That word is, 'Father.' Can you say, 'Father,' Natil?&quot;<br>
