<br>
Inquisitor N`var followed the thin Feir’Dal slave girl through the elaborate hand tooled oak doors to the study of the recently reclusive Ezra Darkreign.  He couldn’t help but feel as if he had just stepped into the nest of a black widow.  <br>
<br>
Ezra stood, back to the door, looking at a large painting which hung over a massive desk.  The painting was of the legendary Teir’Dal Shadow Knight, Z’Tor the Cruel.  The scene was the moment after Z’Tor had bathed in the blood of his life long nemesis, Terrin Silvermoon, Koada’Dal priest of Tunare, when Z’Tor shoved his own blade into himself, ending his life.  <br>
<br>
“What does this story teach us?”  Ezra asked with out turning around to face N`var.  <br>
<br>
“Relevant, this is not.  Think, I do, that we…” N`var began<br>
<br>
“Answer the question!” Ezra demanded, spinning around to face the inquisitor.  <br>
<br>
“Priestess Ezra, I …” N`var began again in protest.<br>
<br>
“Exactly!” Ezra interrupted him again.  “Am I not a priest of our Lord Innoruuk?  Is not part of my sacred and sworn duty to teach and spread the way of our father, the way of Hate?  Now what does this story teach us?”  <br>
<br>
Inquisitor N`var sighed heavily knowing he would not make much progress until he appeased the strong willed cleric.  He stood and looked at the painting trying to recall all of the details of the story depicted by it.  Finally he spoke.  “Teaches us that to become so obsessed with our goals, we should not.  Teaches us, that we…”<br>
<br>
“Wrong.”  Ezra stated bluntly as if he had given her the incorrect answer to a simple mathematics problem.<br>
<br>
“Fine.  Move on we should.  Here to discuss…” He began again.<br>
<br>
“You have to know your purpose.”  Ezra said ignoring the inquisitor’s changing of the subject.  “The spreading of Hate is what a Teir’Dal lives for.  T’Zor could have killed Silvermoon at any time, yet he did not.  His exploits are well documented in his tormenting of the priest of Tunare, and our people revere those exploits.  When T’Zor finally succeeded and taught the priest how to truly hate him, he killed the priest.  Having fulfilled his purpose, he had no more reason to go on living.”<br>
<br>
“Silly, that is.” N`var replied tiring of Ezra’s speech and refusal to use the traditional dialect of the Teir’Dal.  “Find a new purpose, he could…”<br>
<br>
“And risk growing soft?”  Ezra retorted, her emotions beginning to flair.  “What if he never found another true purpose?  He would have lived his life, day by day not knowing what he existed for.  He completed his life when he taught the priest to hate him.  Anything else was a waste.  Is your life so important that you risk your purpose just to live it?”<br>
<br>
Inquisitor N`var silently glared at Ezra.  “Then getting to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> my</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> purpose, I will.”  Ezra laughed out loud but N`var, tiring of the game of cat and mouse she was famous for playing, ignored her and pressed on.  “Demand to know what is going on in your so called guild hall, I do.”<br>
<br>
Ezra raised an eyebrow at N`var.  “What ever do you mean?” <br>
<br>
“Harboring a Knight of the Holy Story within the walls of this great city, are you not?”  He demanded putting the full weight of the authority granted him by the upper class of Neriak into his voice.<br>
<br>
“Does that scare you?” Ezra replied nonchalantly, looking at her fingernails. <br>
<br>
“Nay, it does not.  However, encourage the wrath of the Knights, you should not.  Think this is wise, the noble houses do not.”  He stated as a matter of fact with all the aloofness he could muster.  <br>
<br>
Ezra’s eyes went red with anger.  “Does Cazic-Thule walk in the ranks of the Holy Storm that you should fear them so?”  Ezra said, her voice seethed with anger.  <br>
<br>
“Afraid, we are not.”  He protested.  <br>
<br>
“You quake with fear at the presence of a single monk.”  Ezra spat.<br>
<br>
“Safe, it is not.    We…” He began.<br>
<br>
“SAFE!” Ezra roared in exasperation.  “Sense when has the mighty Teir’Dal been reduced to hiding for their survival rather than fulfilling the will of our God?  When Drazhkahn raises his daughter to be a mistress of Hate and death, we win.  When the monk bitch watches him teach Natil in the ways of our Lord and rages in her heart with hatred against him and curses his name, we win.  When the Knights howl in pain and vow retaliation for the “wrongs” we have committed and lash out at us in fear, in rage and all in the name of justice and valor, but in name only for it will be hate that motivates them… then <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> we win</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Survival is not an option!”<br>
<br>
“Misunderstand you do…” N`var began again.<br>
<br>
“Blind is what you are.  Blind and ignorant.  Fools all who think simple survival is what we were born for.  We are born of hate, breed in hate and die in hate.  You cower and hide in the safety of your stone walled homes and all the while you lose that which made you live… Hate.  You disgust me.  Be gone from my sight or I will teach you first hand the Hate of our God.”  Ezra fumed as she reached out and scratched her nails across his face drawing four lines of blood from his cheek.  “Wear my mark in fear coward, fore if you enter this house again, you will die!”  <br>
<br>
Inquisitor N`var was taken back for a moment then hastily ran from the study.  He ran strait into the massive bulk of the ogre shaman, Dkunblu, who had just happened to pass by.  Not knowing exactly what was going on, Dkunblu made a quick judgement call and roared a thunderous battle cry at the inquisitor, sending him scampering out of the guild house like a terrified jack-rabbit.  <br>
<br>
A few moments later, Ezra stood beside Dkunblu.  “Nice timing, luv.” She said smiling at the image burned into her mind of the “powerful” inquisitor fleeing like a halfling from a dragon.<br>
<br>
“Mez gud at dat.”  Dkunblu said smiling<br>
